(* Tropical Analysis *)
STTropicalAnalysis::usage = "
STTropicalAnalysis[integrand, xvars, coeffs] performs a simple analysis of the singularities of an Euler integral.
It prints the values of Trop(integrand) on the rays of Newt(integrand).
The integrand is described by a product of polynomials in variables xvars with coefficients coeffs.
";
STPreAnalysis::usage = "
STPreAnalysis[integrand, xvars, coeffs] performs an extended analysis of the singularities of an Euler integral.
It returns an association <| trData -> tropical data, rays -> divergent rays, faces -> divergent faces, us -> u-variables |>
";

ConfigureSubTropica::usage = "ConfigureSubTropica[opt -> val, ...] sets external-tool paths (PolymakePath, GinshPath, MaplePath, HyperIntPath, HyperFlintPath, PythonPath, FiniteFlowPath, SPQRPath, FIESTAPath, AMFlowPath, LiteRedPath, LiteIBPPath, FIREPath, FeyntropPath, PolymakeConcurrencyFraction). Only options that are explicitly named are updated; omitted options leave the current global state unchanged (no silent reset to package defaults). The configuration is auto-persisted to $STConfigFile and reapplied on the next Get[\"SubTropica`\"], so you only need to call this once per machine.";

STResetConfig::usage = "STResetConfig[] removes the persistent SubTropica configuration file at $STConfigFile, restoring package defaults at the next package load.";

STSaveCheckpoint::usage = "STSaveCheckpoint[id, state] saves the Association state to checkpoints/<id>.m. Prints a confirmation message with the timestamp.";

STLoadCheckpoint::usage = "STLoadCheckpoint[id] loads the checkpoint saved under id (a string). Returns $Failed if the file does not exist.";

STEchoLinearOrders::usage = "STEchoLinearOrders[id] echoes a table of the linear integration orders found for each face and eps-order of problem id.";

CleanZeroInf::usage = "
CleanZeroInf[expr] applies the standard MZV cleanup chain to expr:
  expr /. zeroInfRules /. ZeroInfPeriod[A_]/;ContainsOnly[A,{0,-1}]:>0 /. zeroInfRulesHALF // Expand
It is also applied automatically by STEvaluate[] when the option \"CleanOutput\"->True is set.
";

(* Hyper-Integrate Subtractions *)
STEvaluateEuler::usage = "
STEvaluateEuler[integrand, xvars, coeffs, hyperIntMode_:All] evaluates the eps-expansion of an Euler integral up to the given order.
The integrand is described by a product of polynomials in variables xvars with coefficients coeffs.
The optional argument hyperIntMode={All,NoOrders,OnlyOrders} specifies if (only) linearly reducible orders have to be computed useful when Maple gets stuck.
";
STEvaluateFeynman::usage = "
STEvaluateFeynman[loops,props,kinematics,dim,order,hyperIntMode] evaluate the eps-expansion of a Feynman Integral up to the given order.
The integrand is described by loops={q[1],...} and propagators {(p[e1]+q[e1]+...)^2+mm[e]}, around dim-2eps space-time dimensions.
Kinematics must be specified as a list of substitution {q[i]p[j]-> ...}. A standard parametrization of the space is provided by the function STGetKinematics
The integral is stripped of the factor Gamma[Length[props]-Length[loops]dim/2] which is also returned.
The optional argument hyperIntMode={All, NoOrders, OnlyOrders} behaves as in STEValuateEuler.
";
STEvaluateFeynmanG::usage="
STEvaluateFeynmanG[graph,kinematics,dim,order,hyperIntMode] is the same as STEvaluateFeynman but accepts a graph as an input.
";

(* Top-level user function *)
STIntegrate::usage="
STIntegrate[] launches the interactive Feynman diagram GUI (calls FeynmanIntegrate[]).
STIntegrate[{edges, nodes}, opts] evaluates a Feynman integral from a graph topology.
STIntegrate[{propagators}, opts] evaluates a Feynman integral from a propagator list.
STIntegrate[integrand, {x,0,1}, {y,0,Infinity}, ..., opts] evaluates a generic Euler integral with Mathematica-style integration limits (default bounds: {0,Infinity}).
STIntegrate[integrand, x, y, ..., opts] is equivalent to STIntegrate[integrand, {x,0,Infinity}, {y,0,Infinity}, ...].
STIntegrate[{pref, integrand, xvars, coeffs}, opts] evaluates from a pre-built integrand tuple (advanced).
Scalar products of momenta in propagators, numerators, and substitutions may be written as p*q, p\[CenterDot]q (CenterDot), or p.q (Dot).
";

(* Interactive GUI entry point *)
FeynmanIntegrate::usage="FeynmanIntegrate[] opens the interactive Feynman diagram UI, \
blocks until integration completes, and returns the result.";

(* Library functions *)
STSaveResult::usage = "STSaveResult[] saves the most recent integration result \
to the local library at ~/.SubTropica/library-local/. \
STSaveResult[assoc] saves a manually constructed result Association.";

STSubmitResult::usage = "STSubmitResult[] submits the most recent integration result \
to the central SubTropica library. No GitHub account required.
Submissions are gated on numerical verification: if $integrationResult does not carry \
a passing STVerify record, STSubmitResult runs STVerify inline (1 kinematic point, \
pySecDec, Tolerance 10^-3) before submitting and aborts on failure.
Backend-tuning options are forwarded to the inline STVerify (\"Method\", \"MaxTime\", \
\"NumSamples\", \"Seed\", \"Accuracy\", \"MaxEval\", \"Integrator\", \"Verbose\", and \
FIESTA / AMFlow / feyntrop tunings). The pass-criterion options (\"Tolerance\", \
\"Order\", \"Substitutions\", \"Dimension\", \"Exponents\", \"ResultIndex\", \
\"LibraryPath\") are locked so the submission gate cannot be bypassed.";

STNIntegrate::usage="
STNIntegrate[{edges, nodes}, opts] numerically evaluates a Feynman integral via sector decomposition.
STNIntegrate[{propagators}, opts] evaluates from a propagator list.
STNIntegrate[cni_String, opts] looks up a library entry by CNickelIndex and evaluates numerically.
Options: \"Method\" -> \"pySecDec\" | \"FIESTA\" | \"AMFlow\" | \"feyntrop\", \"Integrator\" -> \"Qmc\" | \"Disteval\" | \"Vegas\",
\"Substitutions\" -> {s12 -> -7, ...}, \"Order\" -> 0, \"Dimension\" -> 4-2eps, etc.
The legacy option name \"KinematicPoint\" remains accepted as an alias for \"Substitutions\" but is deprecated.
Scalar products of momenta in propagators, numerators, and substitutions may be written as p*q, p\[CenterDot]q (CenterDot), or p.q (Dot).";

STBuildLibraryJSON::usage = "STBuildLibraryJSON[] rebuilds ui/library.json from \
~/.SubTropica/library-bundled/ and ~/.SubTropica/library-local/. \
STBuildLibraryJSON[outputPath] writes to a custom path.";

STSyncLibrary::usage = "STSyncLibrary[] downloads new and updated entries from the \
central SubTropica library. Only changed files are downloaded (incremental sync). \
STSyncLibrary[\"DryRun\" -> True] shows what would change without downloading.";

STBenchmark::usage = "STBenchmark[] runs the benchmark suite defined in \
mgDiagrams-style benchmark catalogue (embedded as $stBenchmarkCasesSource): a dependency check (see STDependencies[]) followed by \
the STIntegrate / STNIntegrate cases exercising the supported input forms and \
backends.  Cases run sequentially in the main kernel; caches are cleared \
between cases so that one case's state cannot poison the next.  The file ships \
two splits \[LongDash] \"Short\" (10 cases, default, ~smoke test) and \"Long\" (21 \
cases, developer regression coverage); pick between them with the \"Suite\" \
option.  STBenchmark[selector] restricts the run to a subset (e.g. \
\"diagrams\", {\"nIntDiagrams\", 1 ;; 3}, or a list of case ids).  Options: \
\"Suite\" -> \"Short\" | \"Long\" (which case list to load); \"Verify\" -> True | \
False (cross-check nIntDiagrams via STVerify); \"Display\" -> \"Stream\" | \
\"Silent\"; \"Baseline\" -> Automatic | None | _String (path to baseline JSON); \
\"UpdateBaseline\" -> True | False | Automatic (bake current run as the new \
baseline; Automatic writes only when no baseline exists yet); \"Report\" -> \
None | _String (write a Markdown report); \"SkipPackageCheck\" -> True | \
False.  Returns Null; per-case details are stored in $STLastBenchmarkResults \
(a list of Associations) for programmatic access.";

STDependencies::usage = "STDependencies[] re-runs the dependency smoke tests \
and prints a detailed per-tool table (status, version, path, install/config \
hint).  Returns the $STDependencies association.  Used as step 1 of \
STBenchmark[]; polymake is required, all other tools are optional.";

STBeachmark::usage = "STBeachmark[args] is an alias for STBenchmark[args].";

(* --- Usage strings lifted from the paper for symbols that were exported
   but previously undocumented.  Fills the 8 drift flags identified in
   docs/public-api-inventory.md. *)

STContinueRays::usage = "STContinueRays[prefsInts, variables, rays] performs \
the Nilsson\[LongDash]Passare analytical continuation along a specified set of \
rays of the Newton polytope, extracting pole contributions before the tropical \
subtraction formula is applied.  prefsInts is a list of pairs {prefactor, \
integrand}, variables is the list of integration variables, and rays is a list \
of integer vectors.  Called internally by STExpandIntegral; can also be \
invoked directly when finer control over the continuation is needed.";

STEspressoFubini::usage = "STEspressoFubini[groupPolynomials, variables, opts] \
finds a linearly reducible integration order for a given set of polynomials, \
using an optimized implementation of the Fubini reduction algorithm.  \
groupPolynomials is a list of polynomial lists (one per counter-term \
integrand); the algorithm finds an order that is simultaneously reducible for \
all groups.  Returns a permutation of variables giving a valid integration \
order, or NOLR if none is found.  Options: \"SolverBound\", \"FindRoots\", \
\"Heuristic\".  Called internally by STIntegrate.";

STToGinsh::usage = "STToGinsh[expr] numerically evaluates hyperlogarithm \
expressions via ginsh, the GiNaC interactive shell (requires ginsh on the \
system path).  Accepts Hlog, Mpl, mzv/zeta, and Log objects, converts them \
to GiNaC format internally, and returns a floating-point approximation.  \
Expressions containing none of these are returned unchanged.";

STToGinsh::unbound = "Hyperlogarithm/Log/zeta arguments still contain unbound symbols `1` after substitution; ginsh cannot evalf() symbolic invariants. Returning $Failed.";
STToGinsh::nonNumeric = "ginsh returned non-numeric tokens `1` (likely an unparseable input or unbound symbol). Returning $Failed.";

STAvailableHeuristics::usage = "STAvailableHeuristics[] returns the list of \
available heuristic names for scoring gauge / linear-reducibility-order \
candidates.  Pass any of these names to STIntegrate's \"Heuristic\" option.";

FeynmanDraw::usage = "FeynmanDraw opens an interactive canvas for drawing a \
Feynman diagram and returns the resulting {edges, nodes} pair in the \
SOFIA / SubTropica convention.  Usage: {edges, nodes} = FeynmanDraw.  \
The returned pair can be passed directly to STIntegrate or visualized with \
FeynmanPlot.";

FeynmanPlot::usage = "FeynmanPlot[{edges, nodes}] visualizes a Feynman \
diagram specified in the SOFIA / SubTropica convention.  The option \
\"LabelInternalEdges\" -> True additionally numbers the internal edges in the \
order they were drawn.";

STSetupKernel::usage = "STSetupKernel[nkernels:3] launches a pool of \
Mathematica subkernels with SubTropica and HyperIntica distributed so the \
kernels are ready for parallel tropical-data and integration work.  Setting \
nkernels to 1 or 0 closes any existing pool and forces serial execution.";

STResetKernelCaches::usage = "STResetKernelCaches[] clears the symbolic \
caches and Mathematica system caches that accumulate across STIntegrate \
calls, on both the master kernel and every active subkernel.  Mirrors what \
a kernel restart would do for the caches that are known to affect result \
correctness or performance: HyperIntica`$LinearFactorsCache, \
HyperIntica`$HyperAlgebraicLetterTable / Counter, \
$NoAlgebraicRootsContributions, plus ClearSystemCache[] and \
ForgetAllMemo[].  Called automatically inside STSetupKernel's warm path so \
re-using an already-launched pool is as clean as a fresh launch.";

STReadResults::usage = "STReadResults[id:\"NP\"] loads and assembles the \
saved face-integration results for the given problem id, reconstructing the \
full series expansion produced by STIntegrate.  Returns the reassembled \
SeriesData.";

STReview::usage = "STReview[] opens the internal review toolkit (?review=1) in \
the default browser. Auto-starts the local SubTropica server if it isn't \
already running, so you can call STReview[] without first calling STIntegrate[]. \
The review tool lets you walk through paper/diagram pairings and verify or \
remove them; verified records are flagged in the public library.json. \
Localhost-only \[LongDash] not exposed to subtropi.ca. Call STStop[] when done.";

STBrowser::usage = "STBrowser[] starts the local SubTropica server (if it is \
not already running) and opens its URL in the default system browser. \
Returns Null on success; returns $Failed only if the server could not be \
started. No native viewer, no parallel kernels, no main polling loop \
\[LongDash] the evaluation cell returns immediately and prints nothing. \
Idempotent: subsequent calls reuse the existing server and reopen the \
browser tab. Useful for library browsing, Review tool access, and diagram \
inspection while keeping the notebook kernel free for parallel work. Note: \
UI actions that would route back into Mathematica (e.g. running an \
integration from the diagram editor) will hang in this mode because no \
main loop is draining the IPC queue \[LongDash] use STIntegrate[] for that. \
The URL is still available as $stServerURL if needed. Call STStop[] when done.";

STStop::usage = "STStop[] shuts down the local SubTropica server if it is \
running. Safe to call when no server is active. The server is also auto-killed \
when the Mathematica kernel exits.";

(* Subtractions *)
STExpandIntegral::usage = "
STExpandIntegral[integrand, xvars, coeffs, regulators_:{eps}, trDataGiven_:{}] expands an Euler integral as a combination of locally finite integrals, using
a combination of Nillson-Passare analytical continuations and tropical subtractions.
It returns a list expansions={{prefactor, subtraction},...} describing the terms in the expansion as a pair prefactor,integral.
The integral is evaluated to a list {{face integrand, face variables},...} indexed by the divergent faces of the Newton polytope.
Each item corresponds to the integral over the integration variables of a locally finite integrand, itself described as a list of terms.
";

STExpandIntegral::notwelldef = "The Euler integral is not well-defined: the tropical evaluation of the integrand vanishes on at least one ray of the Newton-polytope fan, and no regulator-dependent exponent is present to regulate that divergence. Typical cause: a Feynman-parameter integrand without an eps regulator on a subexpression (e.g., raw 1/(x1+x2) or eps/(x1+x2) instead of (x1+x2)^(-1-eps)).";

(* Evaluate Subtractions by HyperInt *)
STEvaluateSubtractionNP::usage="
STEvaluateSubtractionNP[expansions_, order_, vars_ , coeffs_ , id_:\"euler\" , mode_:\"All\"] evaluates an integrand given as a combination of tropical subtractions using HyperInt.
The optional argument mode works as in other STEvaluateII functions. Useful for fine-tuning when Maple gets stuck.
";

(* Evaluate Subtractions by HyperInt *)
STIntegrateSubtractionNP::usage="
STEvaluateSubtractionNP[expansions_, order_, integrationFunction_:Integrate, options_] evaluates an integrand given as a combination of tropical subtractions using Mathematica.
It is possible to use specially designed integrationFunction, such as STIntegrateOrders or STFastIntegration.
";



